<h2>Do a test boil with your new kettle</h2>

<p>
    It would suck really bad if you started boiling your ingredients and your kettle sprung a leak. Everything
    would be too hot to try and fix the leak and you could end up with a serious mess. To test it, add 5 gallons
    of tap water to it, bring it to a boil, and hold it for ~15 minutes. Closely check for anything dripping out.
    You can do this by putting a totally dry piece of cardboard underneath the kettle to make any droplets more
    visible.
</p>

<h2>Read the instructions that come with your ingredients kit</h2>

<p>
    You need a pretty solid idea of exactly what you're going to do when you're brewing. You don't
    want to be making up your hop schedule (discussed in more detail on the <a href="@Url.Action("Index", "BrewDay")">Brew Day</a> page)
    as you go. Pretend you'll have to give a detailed speech about how to brew your exciting new beer recipe.
    You know, like they do on those cooking shows? The chefs aren't just making crap up or winging it.
    They've chopped up their vegetables, measured all of their spices, and they have the steps down in their head.
    This step may seem obvious and trivial, but I'm trying to prevent you from getting all excited, getting
    ahead of yourself, and screwing it all up.
</p>

